---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'Precipitacion de Arenas';

const img1 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/precipitacion/precipitacion-mamu-2024.jpg')).default;
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="Precipitacion de Arenas — Work"
  description="Precipitacion de Arenas (2022–2024). Installation — sand, furniture, security glass, speaker. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 010</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2022–2024 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Installation — sand, furniture, security glass, speaker &nbsp;/&nbsp; Variable dimensions</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <img src={img1.src} alt="Precipitaciones 2024 — Sand falling over tables, MAMU" loading="eager">
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Precipitacion de Arenas — Detail of furniture partially buried in sand ]</div>
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Precipitacion de Arenas — MAMU 2024 installation with 10 tons of sand ]</div>
      </div>

      <!-- Video -->
      <div class="work-page__video">
        <div class="work-page__video-header">
          <h3>VIDEO</h3>
          <span class="label">Polvo Eres — Related video · 2:00 min</span>
        </div>
        <video controls preload="metadata" poster="">
          <source src="/maria-elvira-escallon/video/polvo-eres-obra.mp4" type="video/mp4">
          Your browser does not support HTML5 video.
        </video>
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            Golden sand from the Guamo river falls from the ceiling at different intervals,
            covering surfaces and constantly transforming the state of the room. Domestic
            furniture is gradually buried under tons of sand. The installation creates a
            landscape of slow catastrophe — a domestic interior undergoing geological
            transformation in real time.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The sand's precipitation is both relentless and gentle. It does not crash or
            explode; it accumulates grain by grain, yet the cumulative effect is devastating.
            Tables, chairs, and other recognizable objects of domestic life slowly disappear
            under dunes that form and shift throughout the exhibition. The security glass
            allows viewers to observe this process from a position of proximity but
            separation — witnessing a burial they cannot halt.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            A speaker embedded in the installation introduces sound as an additional
            temporal marker, punctuating the visual rhythm of the falling sand. The work
            engages with themes of displacement, the erasure of domestic space, and the
            overwhelming force of natural processes acting upon human constructions.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The MAMU 2024 version of <em>Precipitacion de Arenas</em> used 10 tons of sand
            for the first time, representing the most ambitious iteration of the work to
            date. This scale allowed the installation to achieve a fully immersive quality,
            transforming the exhibition room into a site where the distinction between
            interior and landscape collapses entirely.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The work connects to Escallon's sustained investigation of time as material
            force — joining <em>In Memoriam</em> (ice), <em>Dispositivos para Ver Pasar
            el Tiempo</em>, and <em>Polvo Eres</em> in a body of work concerned with
            making visible the processes of transformation and entropy that shape both
            objects and lives.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>Precipitacion de Arenas</strong><br>
            2022–2024<br><br>
            Installation.<br>
            Sand (Guamo river), domestic furniture,<br>
            security glass, speaker.<br><br>
            Variable dimensions<br>
            MAMU 2024: 10 tons of sand
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            Encounters in the Dust Factory — MAMU, 2024
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2022–2024). <em>Precipitacion de Arenas</em>.
            Installation. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/precipitacion-de-arenas/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>

<style>
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    }
</style>
